{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ada4db4c08fb0211", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tWARNING: Running pip as the 'root' user can result in broken permissions and conflicting behaviour with the system package manager, possibly rendering your system unusable. It is recommended to use a virtual environment instead: https://pip.pypa.io/warnings/venv. Use the --root-user-action option if you know what you are doing and want to suppress this warning.\n2\t=== PAGE 1 ===\n3\tMMGenre: Benchmarking Singing Voice Synthesis\n4\tacross Multiple Musical Genres\n5\tWenhao Feng ID 1, Yuxun Tang ID 1, Jiatong Shi ID 2, Qin Jin ID 1,∗∗\n6\t1 AIM3 Lab, Renmin University of China, China\n7\t2 Carnegie Mellon University, United States\n8\twenhaofeng@ruc.edu.cn, tangyuxun@ruc.edu.cn, jiatongs@cs.cmu.edu, qjin@ruc.edu.cn\n9\tAbstract\n10\tSinging voice synthesis (SVS) has progressed rapidly, yet its\n11\tability to generalize across diverse musical genres remains un-\n12\tderexplored. Existing benchmarks are heavily biased toward\n13\tpop music, limiting systematic analysis of genre-dependent be-\n14\thavior. We introduce MMGenre, a benchmark for multi-genre\n15\tSVS diagnosis, supported by an automatic pipeline for con-\n16\tstructing genre-aligned music scores. MMGenre spans 10 ma-\n17\tjor genres and 26 subgenres, enabling comprehensive analysis\n18\tof genre-aware synthesis. Extensive evaluation of representa-\n19\ttive SVS models reveals limited genre discrimination: synthe-\n20\tsized vocals across genres exhibit highly similar acoustic char-\n21\tacteristics and weak separability. While zero-shot genre adap-\n22\ttation yields only marginal improvements, lightweight genre-\n23\tspecific continued training leads to substantial gains. MMGenre\n24\tprovides a standardized framework for multi-genre SVS evalu-\n25\tation and exposes critical challenges in achieving genre-aware\n26\tsinging voice synthesis.\n27\tIndex Terms: singing voice synthesis, genre-aware evaluation,\n28\tbenchmark\n29\t1. Introduction\n30\tSinging voice synthesis (SVS) aims to generate expressive\n31\tsinging voices directly from symbolic music scores and has\n32\tachieved substantial progress with recent neural and diffusion-\n33\tbased models [1–4]. Prior research has largely focused on im-\n34\tproving naturalness [5–7], expressiveness [8], and controllabil-\n35\tity [9,10] of synthesized singing voices.\n36\tHowever, singing performance is inherently shaped by mu-\n37\tsical genre, a high-level semantic attribute that is immediately\n38\trecognizable to human listeners.\n39\tGenres such as pop, rock,\n40\tjazz, and classical music exhibit systematic differences in vocal\n41\ttimbre, articulation, phrasing, rhythmic emphasis, and expres-\n42\tsive conventions [11]. In real-world music production and con-\n43\tsumption, genres form stable perceptual categories that shape\n44\tlistener evaluation and preference [12, 13]. Despite its percep-\n45\ttual salience and practical importance, genre has rarely been\n46\ttreated as a first-class evaluation dimension in SVS research. A\n47\tfundamental yet underexplored question remains: how well do\n48\tcurrent SVS models generalize across musical genres?\n49\tThis gap is largely due to data and evaluation limita-\n50\ttions.\n51\tPublic SVS datasets are overwhelmingly dominated\n52\tby pop music (e.g., M4Singer [14], Opencpop [15], ACE-\n53\tOpencpop [16]), offering limited coverage of other genres and\n54\tmaking large-scale systematic genre-level analysis infeasible.\n55\tExisting style-aware SVS studies primarily target lower-level\n56\tattributes, such as emotion, tempo, pitch range, or specific\n57\t**indicates the corresponding author.\n58\tsinging techniques [9,10,17,18], rather than modeling genre as\n59\ta holistic musical condition. Consequently, it remains unclear\n60\twhether current SVS systems truly capture genre-specific char-\n61\tacteristics or simply reproduce surface-level acoustic patterns\n62\tlearned from biased data.\n63\tTo overcome these data limitations, we turn to recent ad-\n64\tvances in text-to-music (T2M) generation [19–23].\n65\tModern\n66\tT2M systems enable explicit genre specification through nat-\n67\tural language prompts.\n68\tCompared to real-world recordings,\n69\tT2M-generated music is easier to scale, poses fewer copyright\n70\tconstraints, and can be systematically diversified across gen-\n71\tres, making it a practical and scalable resource for constructing\n72\tgenre-balanced evaluation data.\n73\tLeveraging these advances, we propose an automatic\n74\tpipeline that uses T2M models to generate genre-aligned mu-\n75\tsic scores, enabling scalable construction of multi-genre data.\n76\tBased on this pipeline, we introduce MMGenre, a benchmark\n77\tfor multi-genre SVS evaluation spanning 10 major genres and\n78\t26 fine-grained subgenres.\n79\tMMGenre significantly expands\n80\tgenre coverage beyond existing SVS benchmarks and supports\n81\tsystematic analysis of genre-dependent synthesis behavior.\n82\tUsing MMGenre, we evaluate representative SVS models\n83\tand obtain several key findings. First, synthesized vocals across\n84\tgenres remain acoustically highly similar, even when condi-\n85\ttioned on genre-specific scores. Second, inference-time zero-\n86\tshot strategies (e.g., style transfer or technique conditioning)\n87\tyield only marginal improvements in genre alignment. In con-\n88\ttrast, even limited genre-specific fine-tuning consistently pro-\n89\tduces substantial gains. These results suggest that genre aware-\n90\tness in SVS is not an emergent, easily transferable capability,\n91\tbut remains strongly tied to training data distribution.\n92\tOverall, MMGenre establishes the first systematic frame-\n93\twork for evaluating genre generalization in SVS and exposes\n94\tfundamental challenges in genre-aware modeling. Our contri-\n95\tbutions are threefold: (1) We propose an automatic and scal-\n96\table pipeline for generating genre-aligned music scores, provid-\n97\ting an extensible framework for constructing controlled multi-\n98\tgenre SVS evaluation data. (2) We introduce MMGenre, the\n99\tfirst benchmark for systematic evaluation of SVS across di-\n100\tverse musical genres. (3) We provide a comprehensive em-\n101\tpirical study of training- and inference-time strategies for im-\n102\tproving genre alignment, revealing the data dependence and\n103\tlimitations of current SVS models. We hope MMGenre will\n104\tfacilitate multi-genre evaluation and encourage genre-aware\n105\tSVS research. Benchmark resources, including dataset access,\n106\tsource code, and audio demonstrations, are available through\n107\tthe project page 1.\n108\t1https://fengjin1117.github.io/mmgenre-web/\n109\tarXiv:2607.06986v1  [cs.SD]  8 Jul 2026\n110\t\n111\t\n112\t=== PAGE 2 ===\n113\tPop\n114\t18%\n115\tBlues\n116\t8%\n117\tCountry\n118\t10%\n119\tRap\n120\t8%\n121\tWorld\n122\t8%\n123\tRock\n124\t10%\n125\tJazz\n126\t8%\n127\tClassical\n128\t8%\n129\tRNB\n130\t13%\n131\tElec.\n132\t9%\n133\tballad-pop\n134\t8%\n135\tfolk-pop\n136\t6%\n137\tsynthpop\n138\t3%\n139\tdelta-blues\n140\t4%\n141\tjump-blues\n142\t4%\n143\tbluegrass-country\n144\t4%\n145\tclassic-country\n146\t6%\n147\tgangsta-rap\n148\t3%\n149\told-skool-rap\n150\t2%\n151\treggaeton-rap\n152\t3%\n153\tafrica\n154\t2%\n155\tarab\n156\t3%\n157\tindia\n158\t3%\n159\talternative-rock\n160\t4%\n161\theavy-metal\n162\t2%\n163\tpunk-rock\n164\t4%\n165\tbebop-jazz\n166\t4%\n167\tswing-jazz\n168\t5%\n169\tart-song\n170\t3%\n171\topera\n172\t6%\n173\tmotown-soul\n174\t4%\n175\tneo-soul\n176\t3%\n177\tnew-jack-swing\n178\t6%\n179\thouse\n180\t2%\n181\ttechno\n182\t5%\n183\ttrance\n184\t3%\n185\tFigure 1: Hierarchical distribution of genres (inner ring) and\n186\tsubgenres (outer ring) in the MMGenre benchmark, with pro-\n187\tportions computed based on segment counts.\n188\t2. Multi-Genre Benchmark\n189\t2.1. Benchmark Overview\n190\tMMGenre is designed to provide a unified benchmark for evalu-\n191\tating SVS under diverse musical genre settings. The benchmark\n192\tcovers 10 major musical genres and 26 representative subgenres\n193\torganized in a hierarchical taxonomy. As illustrated in Fig. 1,\n194\teach major genre is associated with 2–3 representative subgen-\n195\tres to ensure stylistic diversity and reduce pop-dominant bias.\n196\tMMGenre consists of 3,152 aligned Chinese score–audio\n197\tsegment pairs, with a total duration of approximately 4.36\n198\thours. Each segment is constrained to 2–8 seconds, with an\n199\taverage duration of approximately 5 seconds, ensuring compat-\n200\tibility with most SVS inference settings while preserving ex-\n201\tpressive singing characteristics.\n202\t2.2. Data Construction Pipeline\n203\tAs shown in Fig. 2, we construct MMGenre through a unified\n204\tand scalable pipeline that converts genre-conditioned music into\n205\taligned singing voice–score pairs. Starting from a hierarchi-\n206\tcal genre taxonomy, we first employ a text-to-music system to\n207\tsynthesize raw genre-conditioned music. Next, the generated\n208\taudio is processed through a score construction stage, where\n209\tphoneme-aligned symbolic scores are derived.\n210\tThe original\n211\tfull-mix music is retained as auxiliary ground truth for genre\n212\tstyle verification, while the final benchmark data consist of dis-\n213\tentangled singing voice and corresponding score pairs.\n214\tAudio construction.\n215\tWe employ Suno V4.5 [24] as the\n216\ttext-to-music generator within our pipeline to produce genre-\n217\tconditioned music samples via textual prompts. Prompt design\n218\tfollows a hierarchical genre taxonomy and is initially assisted\n219\tby ChatGPT [25], followed by manual refinement to ensure\n220\tclarity and stylistic relevance.\n221\tScore construction. Generated music samples are separated\n222\tinto vocal tracks using Mel-RoFormer [26].\n223\tWe then apply\n224\tSTARS [27] for phoneme-level pitch and duration annotation,\n225\tproducing standardized symbolic music scores aligned with\n226\tsinging audio.\n227\tData filtering. The generated audio–score pairs are further pro-\n228\tcessed through a data filtering stage to ensure reliability. Seg-\n229\tgenre\n230\trock\n231\tpop\n232\tballad\n233\t-pop\n234\tsyth-\n235\tpop\n236\tmetal\n237\t-rock\n238\tpunk-\n239\trock\n240\t...\n241\t...\n242\tGenre tag hierarchy\n243\tAudio Construction\n244\t1\n245\tPrompt Design\n246\t“Metal rock style, male vocal, \n247\tdistorted guitars, fast tempo...”\n248\tScore Construction\n249\t2\n250\tDuration filtering\n251\tGenre inconsistency\n252\tHuman verification\n253\tData Filtering\n254\tPhoneme\n255\ty\n256\tao\n257\tg\n258\tun\n259\t...\n260\tPitch\n261\tD4\n262\tE4\n263\tE4\n264\tG4\n265\t...\n266\tDuration\n267\t0.10\n268\t0.45\n269\t0.15\n270\t0.60\n271\t...\n272\tSuno V4.5\n273\tMusic Generation\n274\tmusic audio\n275\tMel-RoFormer Model\n276\tVocal Separation\n277\tmusic score\n278\tSegmentation\n279\tPitch Prediction\n280\tDuration Prediction\n281\tScore Annotation\n282\tFigure 2: Benchmark data construction pipeline.\n283\tThe final\n284\tbenchmark data consist of genre-conditioned singing voice and\n285\taligned symbolic music score pairs.\n286\tments with abnormal durations are removed, and genre consis-\n287\ttency is automatically verified using MuQ-MuLan [28]. A small\n288\tportion of samples is then checked by human listeners to elim-\n289\tinate occasional artifacts introduced by automatic processing.\n290\tThe resulting singing voice–score pairs are used as standard-\n291\tized inputs for SVS inference in all benchmark experiments.\n292\tBeyond supporting this benchmark, the pipeline itself pro-\n293\tvides a reusable framework for constructing genre-balanced\n294\tSVS data under controlled and reproducible conditions. The\n295\tmodular design of the pipeline allows straightforward extension\n296\tto new genres, languages, or alternative text-to-music genera-\n297\ttors without modifying the downstream evaluation protocol.\n298\t2.3. Diversity Analysis\n299\tAudio-level diversity. We visualize MuQ audio embeddings\n300\tof genre-conditioned Suno samples using UMAP, as shown in\n301\tFig. 3(a). Distinct clusters emerge across genres, and MuQ-\n302\tMuLan achieves strong recognition accuracy (Top-1:\n303\t76%,\n304\tTop-3: 92%), confirming reliable cross-genre separability.\n305\tScore-level diversity. Beyond acoustic embeddings, we fur-\n306\tther analyze symbolic score statistics by examining the distri-\n307\tbution of MIDI note pitches across genres, as shown in Fig. 3\n308\t(b). These systematic differences in pitch range and dispersion\n309\tdemonstrate structural diversity across genres at the score level.\n310\t2.4. Benchmark Validity Analysis\n311\tTo assess the impact of singing data distribution on benchmark\n312\treliability, we investigate whether Suno-synthesized singing af-\n313\tfects the relative evaluation of SVS systems. To this end, we\n314\tconduct a controlled human MOS study comparing model per-\n315\tformance on real and synthesized singing in the Pop genre. To\n316\tminimize confounding factors, validation is restricted to Pop,\n317\taligning with existing SVS datasets.\n318\tBoth conditions share\n319\tidentical musical scores constructed through the same pipeline,\n320\tdiffering only in singing source. Eight SVS models are evalu-\n321\tated, with 35 samples per condition (real and synthesized) rated\n322\tby eight annotators (4,480 ratings in total).\n323\tThe relative ranking of SVS models remains highly consis-\n324\ttent across the two conditions. The Spearman rank correlation\n325\tbetween MOS rankings on real and synthesized data reaches\n326\tρ = 0.90 (p < 0.01), indicating strong agreement in model\n327\tordering. These findings demonstrate that although the singing\n328\tsource differs, synthesized singing preserves the relative com-\n329\tparative relationships among SVS systems.\n330\t\n331\t\n332\t=== PAGE 3 ===\n333\tPop\n334\tClassical\n335\tRock\n336\tRap\n337\tWorld\n338\tBlues\n339\tJazz\n340\tCountry\n341\tElectronic\n342\tRNB\n343\t(a) Audio embedding space\n344\tPop\n345\tClassical\n346\tRock\n347\tRap\n348\tWorld\n349\t40\n350\t50\n351\t60\n352\t70\n353\t80\n354\tMIDI Pitch\n355\t(b) Score-level pitch distribution\n356\tFigure 3: Diversity analysis from audio and symbolic perspec-\n357\ttives. (a) UMAP visualization of MuQ audio embeddings for\n358\tgenre-conditioned Suno-generated samples. (b) Distribution of\n359\tMIDI note pitches across selected genres.\n360\t3. Experiments\n361\tThe central question of this study is whether current SVS mod-\n362\tels can generate genre-consistent singing voices from genre-\n363\tspecific musical scores? To systematically investigate this is-\n364\tsue, we conduct a structured empirical analysis that examines\n365\tgenre behavior from perceptual, representational, and training-\n366\tdynamics perspectives.\n367\t3.1. Experimental Setup\n368\t3.1.1. Models\n369\tWe evaluate a diverse set of representative singing voice\n370\tsynthesis (SVS) models covering both autoregressive and\n371\tnon-autoregressive\n372\tparadigms.\n373\tSpecifically,\n374\tRNN\n375\t[2],\n376\tXiaoiceSing [5], VISinger [3], and VISinger2 [6] are trained\n377\tusing the official implementations provided by the ESPnet [29]\n378\ttoolkit, with Opencpop [15] as the training dataset.\n379\tIn ad-\n380\tdition, DiffSinger [4], StyleSinger [9], TCSinger [17], and\n381\tTechSinger [10] are evaluated using their publicly released pre-\n382\ttrained models from GitHub.\n383\t3.1.2. Evaluation Metrics\n384\tGenre Alignment Metrics. Genre Consistency Score (GCS-5)\n385\tis the core evaluation metric in this work, defined as a 5-point\n386\tperceptual rating that measures how well synthesized singing\n387\tmatches the target genre. Following recent studies that employ\n388\tlarge multimodal models for audio-related evaluation [30–32],\n389\twe adopt Gemini 2.5 Pro [33] as an automatic rater. Given a\n390\tstandardized prompt, Gemini 2.5 Pro assigns a genre consis-\n391\ttency score on a 5-point Likert scale, where higher scores in-\n392\tdicate better alignment. Unless otherwise specified, all genre-\n393\trelated analyses in this paper are based on GCS-5. A human\n394\tagreement check on 100 benchmark samples spanning five rep-\n395\tresentative genres shows strong correlation between Gemini\n396\tand human ratings (Spearman ρ = 0.85, p < 0.01), support-\n397\ting the use of GCS-5 as a scalable proxy for analyzing relative\n398\tgenre-alignment trends.\n399\tSinging Quality Metrics. We report pseudo-MOS predictors\n400\t(SingMOS [34], SingMOS-Pro [35], and SSQA [36]) together\n401\twith a character error rate (CER) metric to measure lyric in-\n402\ttelligibility. CER is computed using the Whisper-WER imple-\n403\tmentation in VERSA [37]. Those metrics are used to ensure\n404\tthat observed genre-related effects are not caused by degraded\n405\tsynthesis quality.\n406\tPop\n407\tRap\n408\tBlues\n409\tClassical\n410\tElec.\n411\tCountry\n412\tJazz\n413\tRNB\n414\tRock\n415\tWorld\n416\t1\n417\t2\n418\t3\n419\t4\n420\t5\n421\tRNN\n422\tXiaoiceSing\n423\tVISinger\n424\tVISinger2\n425\tDiffSinger\n426\tStyleSinger\n427\tTCSinger\n428\tTechSinger\n429\tFigure 4: Genre-wise GCS-5 radar plot across SVS models. All\n430\tmodels exhibit highly similar genre profiles, with strong align-\n431\tment concentrated in Pop-related genres, revealing a systematic\n432\tgenre collapse phenomenon.\n433\t3.2. Benchmark Results\n434\t3.2.1. Genre-wise Alignment Results\n435\tWe report genre alignment metrics of different SVS systems\n436\tacross all genre categories. As shown in Fig. 4, high genre\n437\talignment is consistently observed only for Pop and a limited\n438\tsubset of acoustically related genres, while most non-Pop gen-\n439\tres receive uniformly low scores across models. This trend is\n440\tconsistently reflected in the embedding space. The UMAP visu-\n441\talization in Fig. 5 (a) shows that synthesized samples from dif-\n442\tferent genres form highly overlapping distributions in the em-\n443\tbedding space, in contrast to the clearly separable structure ob-\n444\tserved for ground-truth data. This indicates a relative collapse\n445\tof genre-discriminative acoustic features after synthesis.\n446\tMost out-of-distribution genres with vocal styles that differ\n447\tsubstantially from Pop, such as Rock, Rap, and Classical, ex-\n448\thibit consistently low alignment scores across architectures. In\n449\tcontrast, certain unseen genres with vocal characteristics closer\n450\tto Pop, such as Country, achieve comparatively higher align-\n451\tment. This pattern suggests that, under the controlled bench-\n452\tmark setting, current SVS systems tend to reproduce dominant\n453\tvocal style priors learned from training data rather than con-\n454\tsistently encoding genre-specific attributes as an independent\n455\tcontrollable factor.\n456\tTo further examine the genre collapse phenomenon, Fig. 5\n457\t(b) presents log-mel spectrogram comparisons on the Rock\n458\tgenre, using punk rock as a representative subgenre.\n459\tThe\n460\tground-truth recordings exhibit broadband high-frequency en-\n461\tergy, sharp transient structures, and irregular harmonic spreads\n462\tcharacteristic of punk rock vocals. In contrast, the SVS out-\n463\tputs display smoother harmonic contours and more regular\n464\ttime–frequency patterns, with attenuated high-frequency com-\n465\tponents. Such differences suggest that genre-specific acoustic\n466\tcues are not faithfully preserved in the synthesized results.\n467\t\n468\t\n469\t=== PAGE 4 ===\n470\tPop\n471\tClassical\n472\tRock\n473\tRap\n474\tWorld\n475\tBlues\n476\tJazz\n477\tCountry\n478\tElectronic\n479\tRNB\n480\t(a)\n481\tMel Frequency\n482\tTime (s)\n483\t(1)\n484\t(2)\n485\t(3)\n486\tGT\n487\tSVS\n488\tSVS + Train\n489\t(b)\n490\tFigure 5: Visualization of the genre collapse phenomenon. (a)\n491\tUMAP projection of MuQ embeddings for SVS inference audio,\n492\tshowing substantial cross-genre overlap. (b) Log-mel spectro-\n493\tgram comparison on Rock across three representative samples\n494\t(columns 1–3).\n495\tTable 1: Overall SVS evaluation results on MMGenre, aggre-\n496\tgated over all genres. SingPro denotes SingMOS-Pro.\n497\tModel\n498\tSingMOS↑\n499\tSingPro↑\n500\tSSQA↑\n501\tCER↓\n502\tRNN [2]\n503\t3.25\n504\t2.94\n505\t2.87\n506\t0.47\n507\tXiaoiceSing [5]\n508\t3.43\n509\t3.08\n510\t2.97\n511\t0.69\n512\tTechSinger [10]\n513\t3.84\n514\t3.76\n515\t3.78\n516\t0.59\n517\tStyleSinger [9]\n518\t3.98\n519\t3.74\n520\t3.72\n521\t0.54\n522\tTCSinger [17]\n523\t3.98\n524\t3.84\n525\t3.85\n526\t0.65\n527\tVISinger [3]\n528\t3.94\n529\t3.92\n530\t4.00\n531\t0.25\n532\tVISinger2 [6]\n533\t3.97\n534\t3.98\n535\t4.07\n536\t0.25\n537\tDiffSinger [4]\n538\t4.08\n539\t4.04\n540\t4.06\n541\t0.31\n542\t3.2.2. Overall Synthesis Quality\n543\tTable 1 reports overall subjective quality prediction and in-\n544\ttelligibility results across all compared SVS models, com-\n545\tputed as macro-averages over genres to ensure equal contribu-\n546\ttion. As expected, earlier autoregressive baselines obtain lower\n547\tscores, while more recent SVS systems achieve higher perfor-\n548\tmance across both pseudo-MOS predictors and CER, despite\n549\tthe speech-centric nature of ASR systems, reflecting general\n550\tprogress in synthesis quality and lyric clarity.\n551\tNotably, this performance trend remains consistent even\n552\tunder the newly constructed multi-genre distribution, sug-\n553\tgesting that overall synthesis quality improvements generalize\n554\tacross diverse genre conditions.\n555\t3.3. Mechanistic Analysis of Genre Collapse\n556\tThe observed genre collapse raises a key question: does the fail-\n557\ture originate from insufficient genre-discriminative information\n558\tin the symbolic score, or from dominance of the training data\n559\tdistribution? To disentangle them, we analyze the problem from\n560\ttwo perspectives: (1) symbolic controllability at inference time,\n561\tand (2) distributional bias during training. This analysis re-\n562\tveals whether genre behavior can be activated through score-\n563\tlevel conditioning alone, or whether it is primarily determined\n564\tby learned data priors.\n565\tInference-Time Symbolic Controllability.\n566\tIf conventional\n567\tphoneme–pitch–duration score representations encode suffi-\n568\tcient genre-discriminative cues, then inference-time control\n569\tmechanisms should be able to activate distinct vocal realiza-\n570\ttions without modifying model parameters.\n571\tTo test this hy-\n572\tpothesis, we evaluate two zero-shot control strategies avail-\n573\table among the evaluated SVS systems, namely reference-based\n574\tTable 2: GCS-5 under zero-shot genre control. Improvements\n575\tfrom score-level or inference-time conditioning remain limited.\n576\tMethod\n577\tClassical\n578\tRock\n579\tRap\n580\tStyleSinger\n581\t1.6\n582\t1.3\n583\t1.4\n584\tStyleSinger + Style Transfer\n585\t2.6\n586\t1.7\n587\t1.6\n588\tTechSinger\n589\t1.7\n590\t1.6\n591\t1.5\n592\tTechSinger + Technique Control\n593\t2.1\n594\t1.7\n595\t1.5\n596\tGround Truth\n597\t4.2\n598\t4.8\n599\t4.4\n600\tstyle transfer (StyleSinger) and phoneme-level technique anno-\n601\ttation (TechSinger), as shown in Table 2.\n602\tAlthough minor improvements are observed in certain\n603\tcases, alignment scores remain substantially below those of\n604\tSuno GT. More importantly, the relative gaps across genres per-\n605\tsist, and non-Pop categories continue to exhibit weak differen-\n606\ttiation. These results suggest that the standard symbolic score\n607\trepresentation provides limited genre-specific information, re-\n608\tstricting controllability at inference time. In other words, genre\n609\tawareness does not emerge simply by augmenting inference-\n610\ttime conditioning when the underlying representation remains\n611\tunchanged.\n612\tTraining-Time Distributional Bias. We next examine whether\n613\tgenre collapse is primarily governed by training data statis-\n614\ttics. To this end, we conduct genre-specific continued train-\n615\ting on Rock using two hours of independently constructed AI-\n616\tgenerated data, disjoint from the benchmark set. Under this\n617\tsetting, the GCS-5 score improves dramatically from 1.5 to 4.9.\n618\tThe slightly higher score than GT may reflect subgenre-specific\n619\texaggeration of salient Rock cues (e.g., metal or punk character-\n620\tistics), which can increase perceived genre strength under GCS-\n621\t5. As shown in Fig. 5(b), the fine-tuned model exhibits stronger\n622\thigh-frequency energy and sharper transient structures, closer\n623\tto ground-truth Rock vocals, while the baseline output retains\n624\tsmoother, Pop-like characteristics.\n625\tThe\n626\tsubstantial\n627\timprovement\n628\tindicates\n629\tthat\n630\tgenre-\n631\tconsistent vocals can emerge with sufficient genre-specific\n632\ttraining data. This contrast with the limited zero-shot gains\n633\tdemonstrates that genre behavior in current SVS systems is\n634\tprimarily governed by learned distributional priors rather than\n635\tsymbolic controllability.\n636\tImplications. Taken together, these findings suggest that genre\n637\tawareness in existing SVS models is not an emergent property\n638\tof score-level conditioning, but a distribution-dependent behav-\n639\tior shaped by training data composition. Overall quality met-\n640\trics may therefore obscure systematic stylistic collapse, high-\n641\tlighting the necessity of genre-aware benchmarks for diagnos-\n642\ting data-driven biases in singing voice synthesis.\n643\t4. Conclusion\n644\tWe present MMGenre, a unified benchmark for evaluating\n645\tgenre-aware singing voice synthesis across multiple musical\n646\tgenres under standardized and controlled conditions. Through\n647\tsystematic evaluation, we reveal a consistent genre collapse\n648\tphenomenon: current SVS systems exhibit limited genre dif-\n649\tferentiation and tend to converge toward a dominant Pop-\n650\tlike style. We further show that inference-time control yields\n651\tonly marginal gains, while even limited genre-specific contin-\n652\tued training substantially improves alignment, highlighting the\n653\tdominant role of training data distribution. We hope MMGenre\n654\twill facilitate standardized evaluation of genre-aware SVS.\n655\t\n656\t\n657\t=== PAGE 5 ===\n658\t5. Acknowledgments\n659\tThis work was partially supported by the National Natural Sci-\n660\tence Foundation of China (No. 62576347). We thank Renke\n661\tHuang for insightful discussions and suggestions on music-\n662\trelated aspects of this work, particularly on the design of the\n663\tgenre hierarchy.\n664\t6. Generative AI Use Disclosure\n665\tGenerative AI tools were used solely for language polishing and\n666\timproving the clarity of expression. All technical content, ex-\n667\tperimental design, results, and conclusions were produced and\n668\tverified by the authors.\n669\t7. References\n670\t[1] J. Shi et al., “Muskits: an End-to-end Music Processing Toolkit\n671\tfor Singing Voice Synthesis,” in Proc. Interspeech, 2022.\n672\t[2] J. Shi, S. Guo, N. Huo, Y. Zhang, and Q. Jin, “Sequence-to-\n673\tsequence singing voice synthesis with perceptual entropy loss,”\n674\tin ICASSP 2021-2021 IEEE International Conference on Acous-\n675\ttics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP).\n676\tIEEE, 2021, pp.\n677\t76–80.\n678\t[3] Y. Zhang, J. Cong, H. Xue, L. Xie, P. Zhu, and M. Bi, “Visinger:\n679\tVariational inference with adversarial learning for end-to-end\n680\tsinging voice synthesis,” in ICASSP 2022-2022 IEEE Interna-\n681\ttional Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n682\t(ICASSP).\n